{{copypaste|url=ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC2635388|date=October 2018}}
Thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura (TTP) is a life-threatening disorder characterized by thrombocytopenia and microangiopathic hemolytic anemia accompanied by variable neurological dysfunction, renal failure and fever. It is caused by severely reduced activity of the von Willebrand factor-cleaving protease ADAMTS13. Hereditary TTP, caused by ''ADAMTS13'' gene mutations, is much less common.

Congenital or inherited TTP represents less than 5% of all cases of TTP and the annual incidence is estimated at less than 1/1,000,000. More than 80 different mutations have been identified in families with hereditary TTP.Most patients are carriers of compound heterozygous mutations. Only 15 mutations have been observed in homozygous form, including a homozygous deletion of nucleotides 2930‚Äì2935 in exon 23 of ''ADAMTS13''.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Rom√£o de Souza|first=Valter|last2=Beatriz Cavalcante de Oliveira|first2=Ana|last3=Maria Vanderlei|first3=Ana|last4=Queiroz da Mota Silveira Aroucha|first4=Amanda|last5=Pontes Duarte|first5=Bruna|last6=Nunes Machado|first6=Aureli|last7=Netto Chaer|first7=L√≠via|last8=Wanderley de Barros Correia|first8=Cl√°udia|last9=da Concei√ß√£o de Barros Correia|first9=Maria|date=2018-01-22|title=Inherited thrombotic thrombocytopenic purpura mimicking immune thrombocytopenic purpura during pregnancy: a case report|journal=Journal of Medical Case Reports|language=En|volume=12|issue=1|pages=15|doi=10.1186/s13256-017-1545-3|issn=1752-1947|pmc=5778757|pmid=29357939}}</ref>

