{{short description|Maximum usable amount of land needed for crop cultivation}} {{Use dmy dates|date=November 2016}} '''Peak farmland''' is the maximum usable amount of land needed for crop cultivation ([[agricultural land]]) for a given region (country or an entire world).<ref name=sandetal>{{Cite journal|last=Sandstr√∂m|first=Vilma|last2=Saikku|first2=Laura|last3=Antikainen|first3=Riina|last4=Sokka|first4=Laura|last5=Kauppi|first5=Pekka|date=15 April 2014|title=Changing impact of import and export on agricultural land use: The case of Finland 1961‚Äì2007|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0167880914000899|journal=Agriculture, Ecosystems & Environment|volume=188|pages=163‚Äì168|doi=10.1016/j.agee.2014.02.009}}</ref><ref name=":0">{{Cite book|title=William R. Freudenburg, A Life in Social Research|last=Charles Geisler|last2=Ben Currens|date=20 December 2013|publisher=Emerald Group Publishing Limited|series=Research in Social Problems and Public Policy|volume=21|pages=177‚Äì199|doi=10.1108/s0196-1152(2013)0000021012|chapter = "Peak Farmland": Revealed Truth or Recreancy?|isbn = 978-1-78190-734-4}}</ref> Supporters of the peak farmland theory argue that even with the growing world population, the need for more farmland is decreasing, as food production yields per acre of farmland are rising faster than the global demand for food.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kateprengaman.com/what-is-peak-farmland/|title=What is peak farmland?|date=8 January 2013|newspaper=Kate Prengaman|language=en-US|access-date=24 October 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024090021/http://kateprengaman.com/what-is-peak-farmland/|archive-date=24 October 2016|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref> This is supported by the fact that the area dedicated to farmland in some countries, both developed (e.g. Finland) and developing (e.g. India, China), has already begun to decline.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sandstr√∂m|first=Vilma|last2=Saikku|first2=Laura|last3=Antikainen|first3=Riina|last4=Sokka|first4=Laura|last5=Kauppi|first5=Pekka|date=15 April 2014|title=Changing impact of import and export on agricultural land use: The case of Finland 1961‚Äì2007|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0167880914000899|journal=Agriculture, Ecosystems & Environment|volume=188|pages=163‚Äì168|doi=10.1016/j.agee.2014.02.009}}</ref><ref name=reuters/> Globally, while the total amount of arable land is still increasing, the area of permanent pasture has been in decline since 1998, with at least 60 million hectares no longer grazed.<ref>{{cite journal |author=Poore, Joseph |title=Call for conservation: Abandoned pasture |journal=Science |volume=351 |issue=6269 |date=January 2016 |url=http://science.sciencemag.org/content/351/6269/132.1 |doi=10.1126/science.351.6269.132-a |pmid=26744398 |pages=132}}</ref> It is argued that other countries, such as the United States, are at their peak farmland now.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thebreakthrough.org/index.php/journal/past-issues/issue-5/the-return-of-nature|title=The Return of Nature ‚Äì How Technology Liberates the Environment|website=thebreakthrough.org|access-date=24 October 2016}}</ref>
== Description ==
The concept is usually referenced to the work of Jesse Ausubel and Iddo Wernick.<ref name=sandetal/><ref name="Norberg2016">{{cite book|author=Johan Norberg|title=Progress: Ten Reasons to Look Forward to the Future|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rk34DAAAQBAJ&pg=PA236|date=1 September 2016|publisher=Oneworld Publications|isbn=978-1-78074-951-8|page=236}}</ref><ref name="Bryce2014">{{cite book|author=Robert Bryce|title=Smaller Faster Lighter Denser Cheaper: How Innovation Keeps Proving the Catastrophists Wrong|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mc5nAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA151|date=13 May 2014|publisher=PublicAffairs|isbn=978-1-61039-206-8|page=151}}</ref> They predict that over the next fifty years an area of at least 146 million hectares is going to be released from farming and will probably revert to its natural state.<ref name="Bryce2014"/> As [[Land development|land conversion]] (from a natural state to human use) is one of the greatest threats to the natural environment in general, and [[biodiversity]] in particular, this is seen as good for the environment.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://blog.nature.org/conservancy/2013/01/22/are-we-close-to-peak-farmland/|title=Are We Close to Peak Farmland? {{!}} Conservancy Talk|date=22 January 2013|newspaper=Conservancy Talk|access-date=24 October 2016}}</ref>
{{Cquote|Together with Iddo Wernick [...] we believe that humanity has reached Peak Farmland, and that a large net global restoration of land to Nature is ready to begin. Happily, the cause is not exhaustion of arable land, as many have feared, but rather moderation of population and tastes and ingenuity of farmers. ‚Äì Jesse H. Ausubel<ref>Jesse H. Ausubel, [http://phe.rockefeller.edu/docs/Peak%20Farmland%2018%20Dec%20lecture%20Ausubel(1).pdf Peak Farmland], Lecture for the 18 December 2012 Symposium in Honor of the 80th Birthday of Paul Demeny and his retirement as editor of Population and Development Review</ref>}}
Geisler and Currens note, however, that "Peak Farmland, though newly named, is a long-standing issue" that has been debated by scholars for decades.<ref name=":0" /> The issue deals with two opposing views: one that predicts that more and more farmland will be needed to sustain the growing [[world population]], and the other (the peak farmland view) that progress in agricultural techniques, measured in steadily increasing crop yields from a set amount of farmland, will result in a decrease in the amount of farmland needed to feed the world's population, eventually leading to a decrease in the world's acreage of farmland.<ref name=reuters>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-crops-idUSBRE8BG0QH20121217|title="Peak farmland" is here, crop area to diminish: study|date=17 December 2016|newspaper=Reuters|access-date=18 October 2016}}</ref><ref name="Norberg2016" />
