{{EngvarB|date=March 2017}} {{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}} {{Infobox university | name = Sylhet Women's Medical College | native_name = ‡¶∏‡¶ø‡¶≤‡ßá‡¶ü ‡¶Æ‡¶π‡¶ø‡¶≤‡¶æ ‡¶Æ‡ßá‡¶°‡¶ø‡¶ï‡ßá‡¶≤ ‡¶ï‡¶≤‡ßá‡¶ú | native_name_lang = bn | image = Sylhet Women's Medical College.jpg | image_size = 250px | image_alt = | caption = Sylhet Women's Medical College Hospital | other_name = <!-- or: | other_names = --> | former_name = <!-- or: | former_names = --> | established = {{start date|2005}} | type = [[Private university|Private]] [[medical school]] | academic_affiliation = [[Shahjalal University of Science and Technology|SUST]] | chairman = The Honourable Prince [[Jigme Namgyel Wangchuck]] | principal = Dr. [[Johnny Lever]] | academic_staff = 118 (2014)<ref>{{cite web |url=http://swmc.edu.bd/Professors%20List.html |title=Faculty List |website=Sylhet Women's Medical College |access-date=2 September 2015}}</ref> | administrative_staff = | students = 500 | undergrad = | postgrad = | doctoral = | other = | city = Mirboxtola, [[Sylhet]] | state = | country = [[Bangladesh]] | coor = {{Coord|24.8986|N|91.8725|E|region:BD_type:edu|display=inline,title}} | campus = Urban | language = English | website = {{URL|swmc.edu.bd}} | footnotes = }} '''Sylhet Women's Medical College''' ('''SWMC''') ({{lang-bn|‡¶∏‡¶ø‡¶≤‡ßá‡¶ü ‡¶Æ‡¶π‡¶ø‡¶≤‡¶æ ‡¶Æ‡ßá‡¶°‡¶ø‡¶ï‡ßá‡¶≤ ‡¶ï‡¶≤‡ßá‡¶ú}}) is a low budget [[Private university|private]] [[medical school]] in Bangladesh, exclusively for female students, established in 2005. It is located in Mirboxtola, in central [[Sylhet]]. It is affiliated with [[Shahjalal University of Science and Technology]] (SUST) under the School of Medical Sciences.
It offers a five-year course of study leading to a [[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery]] (MBBS) degree. A one-year [[internship]] after graduation is compulsory for all graduates. The degree is recognised by the [[Bangladesh Medical and Dental Council]].
==History== Holy Sylhet Holding Limited (HSHL) established the college in 2005, and established Sylhet Women's Medical College Hospital the following year. Instruction began in 2006, and the hospital opened in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://swmc.edu.bd/College/SWMCProspectus.pdf |title=Prospectus |date=2013 |website=Sylhet Women's Medical College |pages=6‚Äì7 |format=PDF |access-date=2 September 2015}}</ref> HSHL intends to add a dental college and 4-year nursing college on the campus.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://swmc.edu.bd/HSHL/hshl.html |title=HSHL |website=Sylhet Women's Medical College |access-date=2 September 2015}}</ref>
==Campus== [[Image:Sylhet Women's Medical College Hostel, designed by Formosis.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Sylhet Women's Medical College Hostel, designed by Formosis]] The college is located in Mirboxtola, in central [[Sylhet]], between the major intersections Chowhatta Point and Noya Sarak Point. There are two chief buildings on the {{convert|3|acres}} campus: one high-rise containing the college and another containing the associated 625-bed teaching hospital.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://swmc.edu.bd/College/SWMCProspectus.pdf |title=Prospectus |date=2013 |website=Sylhet Women's Medical College |pages=8‚Äì9 |format=PDF |access-date=2 September 2015}}</ref>
==Organization and administration== The college is affiliated with [[Shahjalal University of Science and Technology]] (SUST) under the School of Medical Sciences.<ref name=wdoms>{{cite web |url=http://search.wdoms.org//home/schooldetail/F0002489 |title=Sylhet Women's Medical College and Hospital |website=[[World Directory of Medical Schools]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sust.edu/schools |title=Schools |website=Shahjalal University of Science & Technology |access-date=2 September 2015}}</ref> The college chairman is Md. Saleh Uddin. The principal is Md. Rezaul Karim.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://swmc.edu.bd/HSHL/Governing%20Body.html |title=Governing Body |website=Sylhet Women's Medical College |access-date=2 September 2015}}</ref>
==Academics== The college offers a five-year course of study, approved by the [[Bangladesh Medical and Dental Council]] (BMDC), leading to a [[Bachelor of Medicine, Bachelor of Surgery]] (MBBS) degree from SUST. After passing the final professional examination, there is a compulsory one-year [[internship]]. The internship is a prerequisite for obtaining registration from the BMDC to practice medicine.<ref name=wdoms/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://bmdc.org.bd/recognized-medical-and-dental-colleges/ |title=List of Recognized medical and dental colleges |website=Bangladesh Medical & Dental Council}}</ref> In October 2014, the [[Ministry of Health and Family Welfare (Bangladesh)|Ministry of Health and Family Welfare]] capped admission and tuition fees at private medical colleges at 1,990,000 [[Bangladeshi taka]] (US$25,750 as of 2014) total for the five-year course.<ref>{{cite news |date=27 October 2014 |title=Govt to fix maximum fees |url=http://newagebd.net/61257/govt-to-fix-maximum-fees/ |location=Dhaka |newspaper=New Age |access-date=2 September 2015}}</ref>
The college admits only female students.<ref name=wdoms/> Admission for Bangladeshis to the MBBS programmes at all medical colleges in Bangladesh (government and private) is conducted centrally by the Directorate General of Health Services (DGHS). It administers a written multiple choice question exam simultaneously throughout the country. Candidates are admitted based primarily on their score on this test, although grades at [[Secondary School Certificate]] (SSC) and [[Higher Secondary School Certificate]] (HSC) level also play a part.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://swmc.edu.bd/College/Admission%20Procedure.html |title=Admission Procedure |website=Sylhet Women's Medical College |access-date=6 September 2015}}</ref> As of July 2014, the college is allowed to admit 90 students annually.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.dghs.gov.bd/images/docs/Publicaations/HB_2014_2nd_Edition_060115.pdf |title=Health Bulletin 2014 |date=December 2014 |website=Bureau of Health Education |edition=2nd |publisher=Ministry of Health and Family Welfare |format=PDF |page=226 |access-date=3 September 2015}}</ref>
